After the two inertial stages aforementioned, on strongly hydrophilic (θeq < < ~57.3° or 1 radian) or completely wetting surfaces (θeq ≈ 0°), a third wetting stage was found. In this stage, the wetting speed is much slower than in the previous two stages, it takes a much longer time for viscous liquids to completely spread and Re < 1. In this long time limit stage, the viscous friction inside the drop is the main source opposing capillarity. The wetting dynamics follows 1/10 power law for small drops of negligible gravity effects (Tanner 1979; Cazabat and Cohen-Stuart 1986; Levinson et al.1988; Chen and Wada 1989; Rafai et al. 2002):5r=R0rμR00.1t0.1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
